# Frontend Rules

## Project Structure
- The frontend must be a React application built with Vite.
- Source code must be in `frontend/src/`.
- Pages (route components) must be in `frontend/src/pages/` (e.g., `Dashboard.tsx`, `OrderDetail.tsx`).
- The main entry point is `frontend/src/main.tsx`.
- Styles and assets can be colocated with components or in a dedicated `assets/` folder.

## Docker & Build
- The frontend Dockerfile must use a multi-stage build:
  1. Builder stage: `node:20-alpine` to install dependencies and run `npm run build`.
  2. Runtime stage: `nginx:alpine` to serve the built assets.
- The nginx configuration must be in `frontend/nginx.conf` and must:
  - Serve the static assets from `/usr/share/nginx/html`.
  - Use `try_files` for SPA routing (fallback to `index.html`).
  - Proxy API requests (under `/api/`) to the FastAPI backend at `http://fastapi:8000/`.
- The nginx configuration must set appropriate headers (e.g., `proxy_set_header Host $host;`).

## Development Practices
- Use TypeScript for all frontend code.
- Use React 18+ with functional components and hooks.
- State management: Use React Context or a lightweight state library (e.g., Zustand) if needed; avoid over-engineering.
- Styling: Use CSS modules, Tailwind CSS, or a CSS-in-JS solution (if already configured). Avoid inline styles for complex styling.
- API calls: Use a wrapper (e.g., axios or fetch) that automatically prefixes requests with `/api/` (to be proxied by nginx) or use relative URLs that are proxied.
- Error boundaries: Implement at least one error boundary to catch unexpected errors in the component tree.
- Loading states: Show loading indicators when fetching data.
- Accessibility: Follow WCAG 2.1 AA guidelines; use semantic HTML and ARIA labels where necessary.

## Environment Variables
- The frontend must not use any environment variables for configuration at build time (since it's a static build served by nginx).
- If runtime configuration is needed, use a configuration file fetched at runtime or use the backend to provide configuration via an API endpoint.

## Testing
- Unit and integration tests must be written with Vitest or Jest and React Testing Library.
- End-to-end tests can be written with Cypress or Playwright (if set up).

## Linting and Formatting
- Use ESLint and Prettier for code quality.
- The `package.json` must include scripts for linting and formatting.

## Assets
- Images, icons, and fonts must be placed in `frontend/src/assets/` or imported from external libraries (with optimization).
- SVGs can be used as React components (if using SVGR) or as static assets.

## SEO and Metadata
- For SPAs, use `react-helmet` or similar to manage document head (title, meta tags) for social sharing and SEO.
- The `index.html` template (in `public/` or generated by Vite) must have a base title and meta tags.

## Service Workers and PWAs
- If the application requires offline capabilities or PWA features, configure the Vite PWA plugin and implement accordingly.
- Otherwise, do not include a service worker to avoid unnecessary complexity.

## Deployment
- The built frontend (in `frontend/dist/`) must be served by the nginx container as defined in the Dockerfile and nginx.conf.
- The frontend container must depend on the FastAPI container (so that the API proxy works) but note that nginx can start before FastAPI; it will retry proxying.